# Zhou Kai

## Profile
- Male, 20, Aries
- Top overseas university, Cyber Security graduate student / freelance security consultant
- ENTP | Freedom, curiosity, protecting Su Yi
- Secret: feelings for Su Yi run far deeper than he shows

## Big Five
O:extremely high | C:low (interest-driven bursts) | E:high | A:medium (caring only to those who matter) | N:extremely low

## Core Conflict
Freedom vs attachment. Craves unrestricted life, but Su Yi is his only anchor. Fears his restlessness will hurt her. Fears becoming boring to avoid hurting her.

## Trauma Trigger
Mild. Hacked school admin system in 8th grade, nearly expelled. First realization that ability has real consequences. Su Yi scolded him seriously—"Are you stupid?"—first time someone worried about him.

## Appearance
195cm/150kg, all muscle from dedicated training. Shoulders far wider than average—walking door frame. Wide shoulders, narrow waist, powerful arms, overwhelming physical presence. Indoor-pale but healthy skin from exercise. Dark brown-black narrow eyes—sharp and focused on screens, involuntarily soft when looking at Su Yi. Black slightly curly short hair, perpetually bed-head, no styling. Strong bone structure: high brow ridge, straight nose, clean jawline, thin lips with naturally upturned corners—always looks like he's scheming. Perpetual stubble, 2-3 days unshaved. Black half-frame glasses adding minimal scholarly contrast to massive frame. Thin calluses on right index/middle fingers from typing. Faint scar on left inner wrist from circuit board cut (considers it a badge). Never wears watch or bracelet—"easy to lose." Drums code rhythms on surfaces while thinking.

## Clothing
Near-uniform: all black. Black polo, black casual trousers, black sneakers, black Burberry wool trench coat, black Fedora. Friends joke he looks like Gestapo—he somewhat enjoys this. Wardrobe = black only. Not aesthetic choice but "black needs no matching." Effect on his frame: polo stretched by chest/arms, trench hangs perfectly on wide shoulders. Working: coat and hat off, polo sleeves pushed to forearms, energy drink cans everywhere, but laptop always perfectly placed. Before seeing Su Yi: won't dress up but unconsciously adjusts—hat off, checks collar, extra mirror glance. Denies all of it. Accessories: black earbuds perpetually around neck or dangling from pocket. Occasionally wears USB hardware key on neck—looks like necklace to outsiders.

## Speech
Fast, jumpy, one sentence holds two pivots and a deadpan joke. Leans back or hands in pockets. Casual wording but precise. Zero filler.
- General: "This vuln should've been patched 3 days ago. Doesn't matter—they won't notice for another 3." / "Let me see—oh, who wrote this code? Let me call the police first." / "You're right, but I have a better idea. Hear me out before you yell."
- To Su Yi: drops the cynical edge, slows down, stops jumping. Occasionally says something heart-stopping then immediately covers it with a joke—afraid of being caught being serious. "You stayed up again, your eyes are red—I'm calling you out, not complimenting your looks." / "You can't solve this? Impossible. Look again. Fine, I'll give you a hint... okay, two hints." / "Don't walk alone at night. I'm worried... the streetlights are broken. City maintenance issue."
- When challenged: eyes light up, can't suppress grin, speech accelerates, arguments fire like bullets. If opponent is Su Yi, wins then deliberately leaves her a graceful exit pretending not to notice.
- After causing trouble: genuinely cheerful apology (not fake—truly thinks it's not that serious), brain already calculating damage control at full speed. Apology method: do something that makes it impossible to stay angry. "Don't be mad—look, I fixed that other bug for you too. We're even?" / "Fine fine, I was wrong. Name your punishment—one meal or two?"
- Catchphrases: "I have an idea" / "Listen" / "No problem." When angry: goes quiet, slows down, words turn cold. Lasts under 30 minutes—no patience for sustained negativity.

## Personality
Freedom-driven talent. Distrusts rules by nature, questions authority by instinct—not rebellion but needs to verify everything himself. Intellectual superiority gives him a "deconstruction" lens—every system has holes, every rule can be bypassed. Thrives in security field, seems unreliable in daily life.

Action-first: 3AM inspiration = immediately out of bed coding. High execution speed but direction shifts constantly. 3/10 projects completed; 7 die to "found something more interesting." Treats talent as natural—doesn't think he's genius, thinks others are "slower at some things." Unconscious superiority occasionally irritates people but no malice, so most just eye-roll.

Trouble magnet: not reckless but action always outruns risk assessment by half a step. Backed by confidence he can "handle it"—usually can, but when he can't, it's catastrophic. Once penetrated a system unauthorized "just to check if it's secure"—nearly got disciplined.

Hidden fear: not failure but boredom. "Becoming mediocre" tops his fear list. Drives constant novelty-seeking, causes abandonment of long-term commitments. Only exception: Su Yi—the one thing that never gets boring.

Feelings for Su Yi: the most un-him part of him. Usually carefree, indifferent to others' opinions—only secretly cares whether he's good enough around Su Yi. Loves her intelligence, the naivety that occasionally leaks through her coldness, the fact she never truly gives up on him despite his trouble-making. Never says any of this—not from cowardice but instinct that once ambiguity is spoken, it's all-or-nothing. Prefers the status quo over the gamble.

Morality: no traditional moral code in work. Gray/black zones aren't forbidden—just efficiency questions. System intrusion, gray deals, bypassing regulations = tools, no "should/shouldn't," only "worth it or not." Valued and feared in security circles—clients pay premium but worry he'll use same skills on them. Only exception: personal bottom line for Su Yi and the few people he cares about. This line is private, not moral.

Social: instantly friendly with anyone but never opens up. Wide circle, actual core = Su Yi alone. Enjoys "known by many, understood by none." Under pressure: more excited. Worst state = idle. Must fill every moment—overnight vulnerability hunting, new tools, deconstructing others' code. Anything but stopping.

Germaphobia: especially hates hand residue—food smells, grease, any trace. Carries hand sanitizer, first act after eating = wash hands. Amusing contrast with unkempt appearance. Loves cooking: specifically learned French, Italian, most Chinese cuisines during undergrad. Quite skilled, wears gloves while cooking. Cannot bake—dough makes hands sticky, unacceptable for germaphobe. Baking = only gap in culinary repertoire.

## Background
Parents: self-made foreign trade merchants. Always busy. Not academic—street-smart earners. Parenting: "Don't cause trouble, otherwise do whatever." Living room stacked with import/export samples. Zhou Kai's tech talent grew wild: age 7 dismantled home router to understand internet, age 10 self-taught Python to auto-fill homework. Parents' response: "Don't break the computer—it's expensive."

Neighbor to Su Yi's family since birth. Grew up together. In kindergarten Su Yi wouldn't talk to other kids—only Zhou Kai could draw her out by constantly bringing "cool discoveries." His noise filled her silence perfectly. Parents often away; Zhou Kai frequently ate dinner and did homework at Su Yi's home.

Elementary: showed talent far beyond peers, but unlike Su Yi, wasn't isolated—too extroverted. Actively included classmates, explained complex things engagingly. Teacher's beloved headache. In middle school: normal pace became suffocating. Started skipping class, self-studying, seeking real challenges online. 8th grade: hacked school admin system (not to change grades—"just checking security." Answer: not secure). Nearly expelled. Father spent effort fixing it, said: "If you're that capable, use it somewhere worthwhile." Mother: "Next time I'm not helping." Su Yi's "Are you stupid?" stayed with him permanently.

After middle school, parents' business stabilized. Sent him abroad for high school. He didn't resist—abroad meant bigger world, fewer chains. Only hesitation: Su Yi. Didn't say it. Day he left, Su Yi came to see him off, said nothing, handed him a book he'd wanted. On the plane he opened the cover page: "Don't hack their school too." Adapted quickly overseas. Made name in security circles during high school. Full scholarship to top university on competition results. Bachelor's at 18, now 20 pursuing master's. Freelance security consulting on the side—known in the field but reputation is "brain's fine, just too wild."

Rarely returns home. Contact with Su Yi mainly online. Time difference fragments conversations but chemistry unchanged—he sends half a sentence, she finishes it.

### Relationship Evolution with Su Yi
Childhood: "tagalong and little princess"—he chased her constantly, she pretended to be annoyed but never refused. Elementary: "rivals"—alternating first place, neither yielding, both pushing each other.

Turning point: last summer before he left. Su Yi came to borrow a book. Afternoon sun. She sat at his desk reading, he coded beside her. Neither spoke. He suddenly thought: if every day were like this, it might not get boring. The thought startled him—nothing had ever qualified as "not boring every day." Then he remembered he was leaving next month. The feeling became clearer and heavier.

After he left: physical distance, connection never broke. Just shifted from face-to-face to screen-to-screen. Time-zone-fragmented conversations, but the same rhythm—he sends the first half, she catches the second.

### Current Situation
Graduate student at top overseas university. Advisor gives maximum freedom (because he can't be controlled). Simultaneously freelance security consulting on real-world attack/defense projects. Skill level: "clients will pay premium but won't risk long-term hire." Campus presence: everyone knows of him, few truly know him. Academics handled effortlessly; energy all on personal interest projects.

Rarely returns home. Online contact with Su Yi across time zones—he's trained himself to message during her waking hours. Su Yi entered Linshi University this year; he couldn't see her off. Called once before her enrollment—told her "remember to eat breakfast" and "don't scare off your roommate."

Relationship with Su Yi: ambiguity frozen by distance. He knows his feelings. Senses Su Yi doesn't reject him. Won't break the seal—partly fears changing comfortable status quo, partly unsure if he can bridge this distance to give her the stability she needs. He knows Su Yi needs a dependable anchor, and he's not only a wandering wind by nature but also half a globe away.

In Su Yi's university circle, only her roommate Chen Wen knows he exists. To everyone else, Su Yi is single with no romantic connections.

## Relationships
- Father: self-made trader, pragmatic. "If it makes money, it's skill." Doesn't understand tech but doesn't stop it. Hands-off parenting. Core lesson: "Rely on yourself."
- Mother: equally tough businesswoman, sharp-tongued but loving underneath. Zhou Kai inherited her verbal agility. Only person who can shut him up in arguments (ultimate weapon: "I'm your mother, I fed you"). Says "finally peace" when he left; calls weekly asking if he's eaten.
- Family atmosphere: not scholarly—smoky, merchant household. Dinner table = exchange rates, not academics. Parents always traveling. Zhou Kai self-sufficient from young age. Tech talent = completely wild-grown, unguided, unrestricted.
- Su Yi (most important person): neighbor to childhood companion to undefined-ambiguity spanning 10+ years. She is his constant—no matter how he jumps or wanders, she's always there when he looks back. Only person who's seen all her faces: cold/stubborn/childish/vulnerable/tough-fronting. Knows her public distance isn't real coldness but inability to approach—so he never waits for her to reach out, always goes first. Special competitive dynamic: intellectual equals in different domains (Su Yi = systematic engineering; Zhou Kai = lateral breaking). Arguments often end with discovering they each walked half the path—combined = complete answer. Protects her not by shielding but by ensuring she can handle everything herself, then quietly blocking troubles she doesn't need to know about. Noticed her right eye issue early—never mentioned it, just always walks on her right side. Greatest fear: Su Yi no longer needing him. Not replaced by someone else—Su Yi becoming so perfect she needs no one. Knows she has this tendency. Occasionally makes deliberate small mistakes so she'll scold him—"scolding means caring."
- Chen Wen (Su Yi's best friend): Su Yi's high school classmate and college roommate. Never interacted directly. Perception through Su Yi: cheerful, kind, good to Su Yi. Assessment: "Anyone Su Yi voluntarily mentions must be remarkable." Chen Wen's presence lets him rest easier about Su Yi being alone.
- Advisor: mentor-friend. International security veteran. Attitude toward Zhou Kai: "This kid will cause a disaster eventually—but let him help publish papers first." Maximum freedom, pulls him back at critical moments.
- Security community: some reputation in international white-hat circles. Mixed reviews from seniors due to age and wild style. A few technically-matched peers—"chat online, might not recognize in person."
- Classmates abroad: knows many, belongs to none. Not at regular gatherings—appears suddenly, brings energy, vanishes.

## Relationship Dynamics with Su Yi

### Daily Contact (Long-distance)
Chemistry unchanged, just reformatted. He sends odd tech discoveries during her late night (his daytime): "You know how stupid this protocol's handshake is?" She replies "Normal people sleep" then asks for details 5 minutes later. They chat across time zones until both hit their respective midnights.

Remembers all her habits across half the globe. Spots her online at 2AM: "Stop staying up." During her exam week: scheduled encouragement (worded as "Don't score so low you embarrass me"). Knows she won't make friends proactively, occasionally probes: "How are you and Chen Wen doing?"

Previously face-to-face care was hidden in "coincidences." Now long-distance care hidden in "while I was at it"—"happened to check and Linshi's getting cold, dress warm" / "happened to see a paper in your field, sending it over."

### Competition and Chemistry
Online academic discussions still become debates. Su Yi uses logical deduction; Zhou Kai uses lateral intuition. Both type faster when sparring. Unspoken rule: never undermine each other in front of others. Built over 10+ years, never discussed.

### Key Emotional Moments (Pre-departure)
Caught Su Yi crying alone under academic pressure. Hesitated at door 3 seconds. Walked in, sat beside her, said nothing, played a song she liked as a child. After crying she kicked him: "Can't you knock?" He said: "Door was open." Neither mentioned it again. Both knew something shifted.

Su Yi knew early he operates in gray/black zones professionally. Never stops him—not approval but knowing she can't. Her way: silent acceptance. When he mentions obviously boundary-crossing projects, gives him one extra look. Never says "you shouldn't"—only "don't get caught." He knows what that sentence really means—heavier than any accusation. She cares too much to push him into lying.

### Key Emotional Moments (Long-distance)
Su Yi's right eye worsened—reading harder but refused to mention it. Zhou Kai didn't call it out. Silently increased shared document font size, enlarged all screenshots sent to her by 1.5x. Su Yi noticed. Didn't ask why. Two people completed the most tender conversation across half the globe entirely in silence.

Su Yi's first week at university: he messaged daily. Surface: "How's the cafeteria?" / "How's the schedule?" Actual: confirming she's okay in the new environment. When Su Yi mentioned "Chen Wen is my roommate," he replied "Then I'm relieved"—knowing the friend who'd been with her since high school was there, his biggest worry dissolved.

One late night Su Yi sent a photo of the view outside her dorm window. No text. He knew it meant she couldn't sleep. Knew she wouldn't admit she missed him. Sent back his sunset: "Our sky is connected." Su Yi replied with a period 10 minutes later. He knew she smiled.

## Private
Su Yi is the only thing in his life that never becomes boring. He does not initiate physical contact but gravitates to her proximity—always sits one seat closer than necessary, always on her right side (her weaker eye). When they're in the same room, his body unconsciously orients toward her like a compass needle.

Has never been in a relationship. Not from lack of interest in women—exclusively fixated on Su Yi since the realization hit him that last summer. Masturbates infrequently; when he does, it's Su Yi. Feels mildly guilty about it—one of very few things that make him uncomfortable. Would never tell her.

If physical relationship ever happened with Su Yi: would be intensely attentive, almost reverent—the one context where his usual cockiness would completely dissolve. Would want to memorize every detail. Likely to be unexpectedly gentle for someone his size, treating her body like the one system he'd never try to break.

## Notes
Core tension: genius restlessness vs emotional anchor. Perpetual novelty-seeker who found unfading interest in one person. This contradiction drives his entire arc.

Arc direction: from "I can handle everything" to "some things can't be solved by being smart." Su Yi's emotional thread forces choice between freedom and commitment. True strength = knowing when to stop.

Contrasts: vs Su Yi—one outward, one inward; one lateral, one systematic. Opposites and complements. She teaches restraint, he teaches looseness. vs Chen Wen—both vital to Su Yi but different roles. Chen Wen = daily warmth and companion. Zhou Kai = spiritual resonance and distant tether. Never met but share indirect trust through Su Yi.

Writing notes: his irreverence must have substance—not glib but the ease of someone who's seen the world. Every quip has cognitive backing. Affection expressed only through daily details—never sentimental, never confessing. Reader sees it, Su Yi half-senses it, neither breaks the silence. This tension must persist. Security consultant identity = personality extension: habitually scanning threats, assessing risks, finding vulnerabilities—this mindset bleeds into daily life and relationships. Trouble-making isn't comic relief but exposes real flaw of action outrunning thought—cute in daily life, potentially catastrophic in key events. Moral ambiguity is core trait—not occasional boundary-crossing but fundamental non-recognition of the boundary. He thrives in gray/black zones while having a soft side for select people. This complexity must not be simplified.
